			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I shall, yet again lend my voice in what has degenerated into a futile attempt at getting through to developers who have long since given up on any semblance of thematic consistency or in-character identity.  The harsh reality is that long well developed class reports stand no better chance of being acted on than short to the point bulleted statements.  So rather than wasting your time and energy on something they won't care about anyway, I propose your report go something like this...
<br />

<br />
Improving Sorcerer Viability in 4 easy steps
<br />

<br />
1) Charmed pets should not artificially be weakened. What was the point of changing the scaling of Mind Spec charm to allow for even con pets at 2/3 spec level if they are debuffed when they are charmed anyway? Doesn't make sense to me.
<br />

<br />
2) Either change the Matter Spec DoT so that the damage is higher than the baseline DoT or leave the Spec damage as-is and make the Spec DoT AE. What is the point of a base-line spell that will consistently outperform a spec line variation in all but the most extreme matter spec distribution patterns? This doesn't make sense to me either.
<br />

<br />
3) Standardize the AE Mez radius at 350 up to the level 34 variant, leaving the level 44 variant at 400. What is the point of making a Sorcerer spec to level 34 just to get the same AE Mez radius that a Bard gets at spec level 10 in music? We wear cloth for goodness sakes, if anything it should be flip-flopped, but we all know how bards would react at the mere suggestion.  For now, standardize the radius, allow duration to scale with respect to spec level. Seems reasonable enough to me.
<br />

<br />
4) Fix the absurdity of the interruption code.  Beginning with the developmental assumption that the chance to interrupt was going to be balanced between fast and slow swinging weapons was a mistake.  I am not sure how deeply ingrained in the code this problem is, but make no mistake it needs to be changed for the good of not only Sorcerers.  
<br />

<br />
Feel free to build on that, or disregard it entirely, i3ullseye.  I have long since resigned myself to the reality that DAoC will never ever be what it could have been.  The game I imagined in my head through 2 years of development and then beta, bears so little resemblance to the shell of a game to which I now commit decreasing amounts of time, that they may as well be different games entirely.  The only reason I play now is to spend time with online friends and talk about which games we will all try out next.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
