			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">What follows is a post I've made to the Kwea, the Mentalist TL. As it may have some bearing on Sorcerers, I decided to share it here.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I wanted to make sure you put into your report something about the lack of effectiveness of spells from lines you've not spec'd highly in. 
<br />

<br />
In my case, my single target Mez simply isn't worth casting as I've discovered that it sticks perhaps one time in three. This was not always the case and seems to have changed somewhere around 1.52 or so (perhaps 1.51). As I think back on what I've read, I seem to recall that this is an issue for Sorcerers as well as I am certain I've read the claim about their 24th level AE Mez that it isn't usable because it rarely sticks. I know Mythic is on a kick to weaken CC of late, but this is going too far.
<br />

<br />
I am not sure what thinking prompted this change, but I do have to take issue with it. The negative for not being highly spec'd in a line is that you don't get the more powerful effects. We do not need to be punished on top of that by having our spell simply not work reliably because that calls into question the entire issue of why we get more than enough spec points to take a line to conclusion. It calls into question spec'ing other than to take a line to completion as well. Split spec'ing becomes a very stupid thing to do as that means that you face a greater chance of being totally resisted.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
